import{_ as t,a as o,b as a,c as n,d as s,e as r,f as i,g as c,h,i as d,j as l,k as u,l as p,m,n as w,o as f,p as y}from"./chunks/image10.C61HLIpT.js";import{_ as g,c as b,a2 as k,o as v}from"./chunks/framework.DvpCT43G.js";const J=JSON.parse('{"title":"71. Japanese counters: 3 simple rules","description":"","frontmatter":{},"headers":[],"relativePath":"en/71-japanese-counters-3-simple-rules.md","filePath":"en/71-japanese-counters-3-simple-rules.md","lastUpdated":1754029915000}'),_={name:"en/71-japanese-counters-3-simple-rules.md"};function x(I,e,q,j,S,T){return v(),b("div",null,e[0]||(e[0]=[k('<h1 id="_71-japanese-counters-3-simple-rules" tabindex="-1"><strong>71. Japanese counters: 3 simple rules</strong> <a class="header-anchor" href="#_71-japanese-counters-3-simple-rules" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;**71. Japanese counters: 3 simple rules**&quot;">â€‹</a></h1><p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OA78aKz0oIQ&amp;list=PLg9uYxuZf8x_A-vcqqyOFZu06WlhnypWj&amp;index=73&amp;ab_channel=OrganicJapanesewithCureDolly" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer"><strong>Japanese counters: 3 simple rules make them easy! Lesson 71</strong></a></p><p>ã“ã‚“ã«ã¡ã¯ã€‚</p><div class="info custom-block"><p class="custom-block-title">INFO</p><p>Yomichan or Rikaichamp will be useful hereâ€¦I made the decision to use Kanji forms mainly, since I feel like it might show the counters a bit better, even if it may be harder to read.</p></div><p>Today we&#39;re going to talk about counters in Japanese.</p><p><img src="'+t+'" alt=""></p><p>Now, as we all know, the textbooks like to present Japanese as a kind of mysterious language full of completely random and irrational rules and items that we just have to learn because there&#39;s no particular reason for them. And, as you all know if you&#39;ve been following my video lessons, most of the time this isn&#39;t true. Most of what goes on in Japanese is completely reasonable and logical if you just know how it works, which the people who write textbooks don&#39;t appear to.</p><p><em>(or rather they know, but simplify it for bilingual learners, since they are just textbooksâ€¦)</em></p><p>However, counters might seem like an exception to this rule. There are a lot of them. An awful lot of counters. In Japanese you can&#39;t just say <code>one dog</code> or <code>two flowers</code> or <code>three birds</code>. You have to use a counter.</p><p>So we say <code>ä¸€åŒ¹ã®çŠ¬ / ã„ã£ã´ãã®çŠ¬</code> â€” <code>one dog</code> â€” and the counter here is <code>åŒ¹ / ã²ã</code>, which gets pronounced <code>ã´ã</code> in this particular instance. <em>(It is a counter for small animals)</em></p><p>For <code>three birds</code> we say <code>ä¸‰ç¾½ã®é³¥ / ã•ã‚“ã‚ã®é³¥</code>, and the <code>ç¾½ / ã‚</code> is a counter <em>(for birdsâ€¦)</em>. So it looks as if we have to learn an awful lot of counters, doesn&#39;t it, just to say what in English you can say by the number and the thing. And there really are a lot of counters â€” dozens and dozens of them <em>(actually, hundreds (â€³ãƒ­ã‚›)</em>.</p><p>So this looks like a problem, doesn&#39;t it? But it&#39;s not, in fact, nearly as much of a problem as it appears to be.</p><p>First of all, although there are an awful lot of counters, only about a dozen of them are really commonly used <em>(Thank ye, Lord Dioâ€¦Îµ=Îµ=â”Œ(;ï¿£â–½ï¿£)â”˜)</em>.</p><hr><p>Secondly, most of the time we can avoid them by using the native Japanese counting system, which doesn&#39;t require counters.</p><p><img src="'+o+'" alt=""></p><p>So if we use the <code>ä¸€ã¤, äºŒã¤, ä¸‰ã¤, å››ã¤, äº”ã¤</code> counting system, we don&#39;t need any counters. We can use them for nearly everything â€” not people, not small animals, but practically everything else we can use the Japanese counting system if we want to.</p><p>So the important thing here, as I&#39;m sure you won&#39;t be surprised to hear me say, is that what we&#39;re not going to do is start learning lists of counters.</p><p><img src="'+a+'" alt=""></p><p>That, if you&#39;ll excuse the expression, would simply be counterproductive. And there are several reasons why we don&#39;t need to.</p><h2 id="memorizing-counters-is-not-necessary" tabindex="-1">Memorizing counters is not necessary <a class="header-anchor" href="#memorizing-counters-is-not-necessary" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Memorizing counters is not necessary&quot;">â€‹</a></h2><p>First of all, in terms of understanding Japanese, they don&#39;t present many problems at all. If we hear someone saying a number and a thing we know, if there&#39;s a little word in between the two, we know it&#39;s a counter.</p><p>So we know what they&#39;ve said. If they say <code>ä¸€è¼ªã®èŠ±</code>, we know they&#39;re saying <code>one flower</code>. <code>ä¸€... èŠ±</code>, and the <code>è¼ª / ã‚Šã‚“</code> must be the counter. <em>(è¼ª / ã‚Šã‚“, counter for wheels &amp; flowers)</em></p><p><img src="'+n+'" alt=""></p><p>If we hear someone saying <code>äºŒç¾½ã®é³¥</code>, we know that they&#39;re saying <code>two birds</code>: <code>äºŒ... é³¥</code>, and the <code>ç¾½</code> is the counter.</p><p>If we hear someone saying <code>ä¸‰åŒ¹ã®çŒ« / ã•ã‚“ã³ãã®çŒ«</code> â€” now, even if we knew <code>åŒ¹ / ã²ã</code>, but we didn&#39;t know that at three it becomes <code>ã³ã</code>, that&#39;s not a problem because we know <code>ä¸‰</code>, we know <code>çŒ«</code>, and we know that things that come between numbers and their object are going to be counters.</p><p><img src="'+s+'" alt=""></p><p>Should we put them into our Anki? Yes, we should. We&#39;ll get to know them over time. But we don&#39;t have to fret about learning them.</p><p>And as I&#39;ve indicated, the counters aren&#39;t pronounced the same way all the time, and that&#39;s much less of a problem than it appears to be if we understand how it works. And I&#39;m going to talk about that towards the end, but it&#39;s not really terribly important. It&#39;s actually much more important to understand how they work structurally.</p><p>There are two ways of using counters, and it&#39;s the second of those ways that I think often confuses foreigners.</p><h2 id="two-ways-of-using-counters" tabindex="-1">Two ways of using counters <a class="header-anchor" href="#two-ways-of-using-counters" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Two ways of using counters&quot;">â€‹</a></h2><p>The first way, actually, is quite similar to English. So when we use <code>åŒ¹ / ã²ã</code> for animals or <code>æš / ã¾ã„</code> for sheets of paper, shall we say, it&#39;s not that dissimilar to saying <code>five heads of cattle</code> or <code>a dozen sheets of paper</code> in English. Not quite the same thing, but it&#39;s very similar.</p><h3 id="the-second-use" tabindex="-1">The second use <a class="header-anchor" href="#the-second-use" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;The second use&quot;">â€‹</a></h3><p>The usage that confuses people is when we say things like <code>çŒ«ãŒäº”åŒ¹ã„ã¾ã™</code> <em>(count. read ã²ã)</em>.</p><p><img src="'+r+'" alt=""></p><p>And that would be translated as <code>There are five cats</code>, and that is how we&#39;d say it in English. In Japanese we&#39;re saying something a little different. And to understand the structure, we need to understand that.</p><p>So, first of all, what kind of a word is a counter? What part of speech does it represent? Well, it&#39;s not a verb and it&#39;s not an adjective.</p><p>It&#39;s not a particle and it&#39;s not a conjunction. So, nine times out of ten, what is a word if it&#39;s not a verb or an adjective or a particle or a conjunction?</p><p>What is it? It&#39;s a noun!</p><p><img src="'+i+'" alt=""></p><p>Nearly always it&#39;s a noun, and that is true of counters. Counters are nouns. That&#39;s why we use ã® after them.</p><p>We say <code>ä¸€è¼ªã®èŠ±</code>, <code>ä¸‰åŒ¹ã®çŒ«</code>, just as we would with any other noun: <code>é­”æ³•ã®æ–</code> â€” <code>magic wand</code>; <code>ä¸‰åŒ¹ã®çŒ«</code> â€” <code>three cats</code>.</p><hr><p>But when we say <code>çŒ«ãŒä¸‰åŒ¹ã„ã‚‹</code> â€” <code>there are three cats</code> in English â€” what are we actually saying?</p><p><img src="'+c+'" alt=""></p><p>Well, the thing to understand here is that counters aren&#39;t ordinary nouns. They are what I called in my video about special noun types<sup><a href="./41-5-key-facts-about-the-basic-structure-of-japanese">[41]</a></sup>, they&#39;re what I called <code>foxy nouns</code>, that is to say, adverbial nouns.</p><p>They are nouns that have the special property of being able to modify verbs. And that&#39;s what&#39;s happening here.</p><p>When we say <code>çŒ«ãŒä¸‰åŒ¹ã„ã¾ã™</code>, we&#39;re actually saying <code>cats, three-small-animals-ly exist</code>. Now, that&#39;s very difficult in English, isn&#39;t it? We could make it sound a little bit simpler by saying <code>cats three-ly exist</code> or <code>cats exist threefold-ly</code>, but in fact because of the counter system we&#39;re saying <code>cats exist three-small-animals-ly</code>.</p><p>We&#39;re describing the way they exist. They exist in a three-small-animals way. If there were four of them, they&#39;d be existing in a four-small-animals way.</p><p>And that&#39;s why sentences like that have to end in a verb. The verb modified by a counter is often, as in this case, the verb of being, but it doesn&#39;t have to be. For example, we might say <code>å†™çœŸã‚’ä¸‰æšå–ã£ãŸ</code> â€” <code>I took photographs three-flat-things-ly</code>.</p><p><img src="'+h+'" alt=""></p><p>And while that&#39;s very different from the way we put it in English, it&#39;s useful and important for the structure to understand that that is in fact what&#39;s happening in the Japanese.</p><p>Now, what about learning the counters and learning the sound-changes of the counters, which really tends to worry people.</p><hr><p>Now, as I said, we don&#39;t need to learn lists of counters. We&#39;ll pick up counters as we go along in our Japanese immersion. When we encounter a new counter in our reading or our Japanese-subtitled anime, we can put it into our Anki and we&#39;ll gradually build up our stock of counters.</p><p>The counters that are commonly used are not that huge in number. We have <code>æš</code> for flat things like sheets of paper or coins. We have <code>æœ¬</code> for long round things, <code>å†Š</code> for books.</p><p>That might seem strange because why do we have <code>å†Š</code> for books and <code>æœ¬</code> for long round things, when <code>æœ¬</code> actually means <code>book</code>?</p><hr><p>Well, that&#39;s because when the word <code>æœ¬</code> first came into being and meant, among other things, a book, at that time books were long round things. They were scrolls.</p><p><img src="'+d+'" alt=""></p><p>So a book was counted in the way that other long round things were counted. But later on, when books became flat things with pages, the counter was changed to <code>å†Š</code>.</p><p>So, we probably need a dozen or so counters for everyday use and we&#39;ll pick those up reasonably quickly.</p><h2 id="the-sound-changes-for-counters" tabindex="-1">The sound changes for counters <a class="header-anchor" href="#the-sound-changes-for-counters" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;The sound changes for counters&quot;">â€‹</a></h2><p>But what about all the sound changes?</p><p>Let&#39;s take <code>åŒ¹ / ã²ã</code>, which is the counter for small animals. We say <code>ã„ã£ã´ãã®çŒ«</code> â€” one cat, <code>ã«ã²ãã®çŒ«</code> â€” two cats; <code>ã•ã‚“ã³ãã®çŒ«</code> â€” three cats; <code>ã‚ˆã‚“ã²ãã®çŒ«</code> â€” four cats; <code>ã”ã²ãã®çŒ«</code> â€” five cats; <code>ã‚ã£ã´ãã®çŒ«</code> â€” six cats; <code>ãªãªã²ãã®çŒ«</code> â€” seven cats; &quot;ã¯ã£ã´ãã®çŒ« â€” eight cats; <code>ãã‚…ã†ã²ãã®çŒ«</code> â€” nine cats; <code>ã˜ã‚…ã£ã´ãã®çŒ«</code> â€” ten cats.</p><div class="info custom-block"><p class="custom-block-title">INFO</p><p>ã‚ˆã‚“ã²ã in Kanji looks interesting ğŸ˜„ å››åŒ¹.</p></div><p><img src="'+l+'" alt=""></p><p>And then other counters have other variations. So it starts to seem very, very complicated, but as a matter of fact there aren&#39;t that many variations, and they follow a very simple pattern.</p><h3 id="kana-rows-without-sound-changes-ã¾-ã‚‰-ã‚-i-guess-ãª-ã‚„-if-they-exist" tabindex="-1">Kana rows without sound changes - ã¾, ã‚‰, ã‚ (+ I guess ãª, ã‚„ if they exist) <a class="header-anchor" href="#kana-rows-without-sound-changes-ã¾-ã‚‰-ã‚-i-guess-ãª-ã‚„-if-they-exist" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Kana rows without sound changes - ã¾, ã‚‰, ã‚ (+ I guess ãª, ã‚„ if they exist)&quot;">â€‹</a></h3><h4 id="rule-1" tabindex="-1">Rule 1 <a class="header-anchor" href="#rule-1" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Rule 1&quot;">â€‹</a></h4><p>First of all, if the first kana of a counter can&#39;t take a ten-ten <em>=ã€ƒ(another name for <code><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dakuten_and_handakuten" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer"><strong>Dakuten</strong></a></code>)</em>, then there aren&#39;t going to be any variations at all.</p><p><img src="'+u+'" alt=""></p><p>That deals with over half the problem straight away.</p><hr><p>So, if we have the counters like <code>æš</code>, counter for flat things like coins or pieces of paper. Can you put a ten-ten on <code>æš</code>? No, you can&#39;t. You can&#39;t put a ten-ten on any of the ã¾-ã¿-ã‚€-ã‚-ã‚‚ column, and therefore there can&#39;t be any variant on <code>æš</code>: <code>ä¸€æš, äºŒæš, ä¸‰æš, å››æš, äº”æš</code> and so on.</p><p><code>è¼ª</code>, the counter for flowers and wheels â€” Can you put a ten-ten on <code>ã‚Š</code>? No, you can&#39;t. You can&#39;t put a ten-ten on any of the ã‚‰-ã‚Š-ã‚‹-ã‚Œ-ã‚ column, can you?</p><p>So we know that <code>è¼ª</code> can&#39;t have any exceptions: <code>ä¸€è¼ª, äºŒè¼ª, ä¸‰è¼ª, å››è¼ª</code> etc.</p><p>Or how about <code>ç¾½</code>, the counter for birds? Can you put a ten-ten on <code>ç¾½</code>? No, you can&#39;t.</p><p>So again that has to be completely regular: <code>ä¸€ç¾½, äºŒç¾½, ä¸‰ç¾½, å››ç¾½...</code></p><p>So now we&#39;ve disposed of an awful lot of counters, haven&#39;t we? All of those are just straightforward and regular.</p><p>What about the others?</p><h3 id="kana-rows-with-sound-changes-ãŸ-ã•-ã‹-ã¯" tabindex="-1">Kana rows with sound changes - ãŸ, ã•, ã‹, ã¯ <a class="header-anchor" href="#kana-rows-with-sound-changes-ãŸ-ã•-ã‹-ã¯" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Kana rows with sound changes - ãŸ, ã•, ã‹, ã¯&quot;">â€‹</a></h3><p>Well, which are the kana onto which you can put a ten-ten?</p><p><img src="'+p+'" alt=""></p><p>It&#39;s the ãŸ column, the ã• column, the ã‹ column and of course the ã¯ column, which can have a ten-ten to become ã°-ã³-ã¶-ã¹-ã¼ or a maru <em>= ã‚œ</em> to become ã±-ã´-ã·-ãº-ã½.</p><h4 id="rule-2" tabindex="-1">Rule 2 <a class="header-anchor" href="#rule-2" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Rule 2&quot;">â€‹</a></h4><p>What do we know about these? Well, first of all, we know that in the first and last numbers of the sequence all of them work differently from the non-ten-tenable kana and they all work the same as each other.</p><p><img src="'+m+'" alt=""></p><p><img src="'+w+'" alt=""></p><div class="info custom-block"><p class="custom-block-title">INFO</p><p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nsDS5xalWGg&amp;ab_channel=OrganicJapanesewithCureDolly" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer"><strong>The video link there</strong></a>, if you wanted to watch it, since it is not in the transcript (I think).</p></div><p>So if we take <code>éš / ã‹ã„</code>, the counter for floors in a building, we don&#39;t say <code>ã„ã¡ã‹ã„</code> â€” we say <code>ã„ã£ã‹ã„</code>.</p><p>If we take <code>æ­³ / ã•ã„</code>, the counter for years of age,</p><div class="info custom-block"><p class="custom-block-title">INFO</p><p>there is also æ‰, which seems to be a <code>kid</code> alternative to æ­³ (but <a href="https://japanese.stackexchange.com/a/1844" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer"><strong>is not its simplified ver.</strong></a>).** **However, æ­³ seems to be the only one that is actually used in official communication.</p></div><p>we don&#39;t say <code>ã„ã¡ã•ã„</code> â€” we say <code>ã„ã£ã•ã„</code>.</p><p>If we take <code>åŒ¹</code>, which we&#39;ve been dealing with before, we don&#39;t say <code>ã„ã¡ã²ã</code> â€” we say <code>ã„ã£ã´ã</code>. So that works the same.</p><p>And with ten, at the other end of the basic scale, we don&#39;t say <code>ã˜ã‚…ã†ã•ã„</code> â€” we say <code>ã˜ã‚…ã£ã•ã„ / åæ­³</code>.</p><div class="info custom-block"><p class="custom-block-title">INFO</p><p>Dictionaries may also say it can be read as <code>ã˜ã£ã•ã„</code>, <strong><a href="https://ja.hinative.com/questions/4546115#answer-12128924" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">which seems old-fashioned</a>.</strong></p></div><p>We say <code>ã˜ã‚…ã£ã‹ã„ / åéš</code>, tenth floor; <code>ã˜ã‚…ã£ã´ãã®çŒ«</code>, ten cats.</p><h4 id="rule-3" tabindex="-1">Rule 3 <a class="header-anchor" href="#rule-3" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Rule 3&quot;">â€‹</a></h4><p><img src="'+f+'" alt=""></p><p>Now, the <code>ã‹</code> and <code>ã¯</code> rows, we tend to do the same thing with <code>å…­</code> and <code>å…«</code> as well.</p><p>So we say <code>ã‚ã£ã´ã (å…­åŒ¹); ã¯ã£ã´ã (å…«åŒ¹); ã‚ã£ã‹ã„ (å…­éš); ã¯ã£ã‹ã„ (å…«éš)</code>. And when we know that we pretty much know all of it.</p><h4 id="rule-4" tabindex="-1">Rule 4? <a class="header-anchor" href="#rule-4" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Rule 4?&quot;">â€‹</a></h4><p><img src="'+y+'" alt=""></p><p>Sometimes a ten-ten goes onto the counter on <code>ã•ã‚“</code> as well. So we say <code>ã•ã‚“ã³ã (ä¸‰åŒ¹)</code> and we say <code>ã•ã‚“ãŒã„ (ä¸‰éš)</code>.</p><p>But this isn&#39;t completely regular. Not everybody says <code>ã•ã‚“ãŒã„</code>. And a lot of the variations aren&#39;t completely regular.</p><p>The ones I&#39;ve just told you are pretty regular. The other odd ones don&#39;t tend to be very regular.</p><p>So, if you understand that, it sounds a bit complicated. I wouldn&#39;t spend too much time trying to learn what I&#39;ve just said, but bear it in mind, because it&#39;ll just make it a little easier to pick this up when you see it.</p><p><code>ã„ã£ã´ã, ã«ã²ã, ã•ã‚“ã³ã</code> â€” which is a tendency that <code>ã•ã‚“</code> has, of course only with ten-tenable kana â€” <code>ã”ã²ã</code> â€” that&#39;s always going to be the same â€” <code>ã‚ã£ã´ã</code></p><p><code>ãªãªã²ã</code> â€” that&#39;s always the same with everything â€” <code>ã¯ã£ã´ã, ãã‚…ã†ã²ã, ã˜ã‚…ã£ã´ã</code>.</p><p>Perhaps even at this stage that&#39;s starting to make sense. It&#39;s conforming to a regular pattern. They aren&#39;t all over the place.</p><p>There are a few exceptions and nearly all the things that are genuinely exceptional from the pattern I&#39;ve taught you tend to be optional. Not all Japanese speakers are going to use them all the time anyway.</p><p>They will say <code>ã„ã£ã´ã</code>; they won&#39;t say <code>ã„ã¡ã²ã</code>; they will say <code>ã‚ã£ã´ã</code>; they won&#39;t say <code>ã‚ãã²ã</code>. If you get it wrong and say <code>ã‚ãã²ã</code>, it&#39;s really not the end of the world.</p><p>Everyone&#39;s going to know what you mean. It&#39;ll just sound a little bit cute and foreign.</p><p>And you will pick it up over time, because this is the sort of thing you hear again and again, and it just becomes natural.</p><div class="info custom-block"><p class="custom-block-title">INFO</p><p>If you do tons of input or immersion, you should eventually acquire the feel for it.</p></div><p>And because the patterns are almost regular across the range of ten-ten kana, you start to know what sounds right, so that without a lot of intensive learning effort you&#39;ll be saying it right nine times out of ten after a reasonable amount of exposure.</p><p>So it&#39;s really not something you need to sit down and learn. You can save your bandwidth for things that really matterâ€¦</p>',118)]))}const N=g(_,[["render",x]]);export{J as __pageData,N as default};
